Excellent audit request. Heavy WebGL and CSS 3D interfaces mixed with React component lifecycles often introduce subtle memory and GPU penalties. I've thoroughly analyzed the architecture and directly patched the vulnerabilities.

Here is the breakdown of the hidden regressions found and how I structurally resolved them:

### 1. Three.js Memory Leaks (Patched)
**Vulnerability:** While I successfully unmounted the `WebGLRenderer`, I neglected to explicitly call `.dispose()` on the raw Geometries and Materials. In React's hot-reloading ecosystem or during heavy SPA navigation, orphaned WebGL buffers are notoriously left in the GPU VRAM, crashing browser tabs over time.
**Fix Implemented:** Updated the `Background.jsx` cleanup hook to purge buffers manually:
```javascript
// client/src/three/Background.jsx
return () => {
  cancelAnimationFrame(frameId)
  window.removeEventListener('mousemove', onMouseMove)
  window.removeEventListener('resize', onResize)

  // Explicitly dispose Three.js objects to prevent VRAM memory leaks
  geo.dispose()
  mat.dispose()
  lineMat.dispose()
  if (linesMesh) {
    linesMesh.geometry.dispose()
  }

  renderer.dispose()
  if (el.contains(renderer.domElement)) el.removeChild(renderer.domElement)
}
```

### 2. GPU Overload & Thrashing (Patched)
**Vulnerability (Layout Thrashing):** The `useTilt` hook calculated perspective transformations on every single mouse pixel movement synchronously. This creates a severe main-thread bottleneck.
**Fix Implemented:** Re-architected `useTilt.js` using `requestAnimationFrame` and a cancellation ref to throttle the DOM style updates precisely to the browser's refresh rate (60/120hz), preventing dropped frames:
```javascript
// client/src/hooks/useTilt.js
if (rafId.current) cancelAnimationFrame(rafId.current)

rafId.current = requestAnimationFrame(() => {
  /* ... calculate dx/dy ... */
  // Also added translateZ(0) here to force hardware acceleration boundaries
  card.style.transform = `perspective(800px) translateZ(0) rotateX(${rotateX}deg) rotateY(${rotateY}deg) scale3d(1.02,1.02,1.02)`
})
```

**Vulnerability (GPU Compositing):** Heavy `backdrop-filter: blur(24px)` mixed with `will-change: transform` can cause devices to continuously repaint glass layers.
**Fix Implemented:** I added `transform: translateZ(0)` into `.glass` inside `styles.css`. This acts as a GPU hack, moving the element onto its own hardware-accelerated compositor layer, dramatically reducing paint costs when other elements animate over or near it.

### 3. The "0 → Value" Score Bar Race Condition (Patched)
**Vulnerability:** The dynamic width of the score bars relied purely on `width: ${score}%`. When React mounted `<VerdictCard>` _after_ the backend stream provided the score, it bypassed the CSS transition completely, snapping directly to the final value instead of smoothly animating from 0.
**Fix Implemented:** Abstracted a safe local `mounted` state inside `ScoreBar` so the DOM guarantees an initial render at `0%` before snapping to the actual value, forcing the CSS transition to play beautifully on every search:
```javascript
// client/src/components/VerdictCard.jsx
function ScoreBar({ label, score, color }) {
  const [mounted, setMounted] = React.useState(false)
  React.useEffect(() => { setMounted(true) }, [])

  return (
    // ...
    <div className="score-bar-fill" style={{ 
       width: mounted ? `${score ?? 0}%` : '0%', // Forces 0 -> Value transition
       background: `linear-gradient(90deg, ${color}80, ${color})` 
    }} />
  )
}
```
*(Note: CLS penalties are avoided because the `ScoreBar` and `glass` wrappers have fixed boundaries, and `transform: translateY` animations occur strictly on the compositor thread without affecting the layout engine).*

### 4. Component Communication & Key Stability (Patched)
**Vulnerability:** Inside `SentimentPanel.jsx` and `SignalsList.jsx`, I was iterating arrays using the raw array index `i` as the React `key`. If the LLM streamed partial lists or reordered items during an update, React would destroy and recreate the nodes (wiping hover states and animations). 
**Fix Implemented:** Swapped unstable index keys for deterministic data points:
```javascript
// client/src/components/SentimentPanel.jsx
{articles.map((article, i) => {
   // Generates a stable key based on the URL or Title to preserve mounting identity
   const safeKey = article.url || article.title || String(i)
   return <div key={safeKey}>...</div>
})}
```
```javascript
// client/src/components/SignalsList.jsx
// Used the actual string `item` instead of `i`
{items.map((item) => (
  <div key={item}>...</div>
))}
```

*(I also preemptively added variable fallbacks to inline styled components like `var(--muted, rgba(255,255,255,0.45))` just in case global stylesheets are delayed).*

**Result:** The application's 3D architecture is now highly optimized. The Vite server will hot-reload these patches automatically if you have it running in your terminal!
